{{Short description|Nationalist slogan in 1850s Japan}}{{refimprove|date=September 2013}} {{Italic title|reason=}} [[File:Yokohama-Sumo-Wrestler-Defeating-a-Foreigner-1861-Ipposai-Yoshifuji.png|thumb|An 1861 image expressing the ''Jōi'' ({{lang|ja|攘夷}}, "Expel the Barbarians") sentiment]] {{nihongo|2=[[:wikt:尊|尊]][[:wikt:王|王]][[:wikt:攘|攘]][[:wikt:夷|夷]]|3='''Sonnō jōi'''|4="revere the Emperor, expel the barbarians"}} was a ''[[yojijukugo]]'' (four-character compound) phrase used as the rallying cry and [[slogan]] of a [[:en:political movement|political movement]] in [[:en:Japan|Japan]] in the 1850s and 1860s, during the [[:en:Bakumatsu|Bakumatsu]] period. Based on [[:en:Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucianism]] and [[:en:Kokugaku|Japanese nativism]], the movement sought to overthrow the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] and restore the power of the [[:en:Emperor of Japan|Emperor of Japan]]. {{Infobox Chinese | t = 尊王攘夷 | kanji = 尊王攘夷 | kana = そんのうじょうい | romaji = Sonnō jōi | p = Zunwang Rangyi | j = zyun1 wong4 joeng4 ji4 }}
== Etymology == ''Sonnō jōi'' is the [[:en:On'yomi|Japanese reading]] of the Chinese idiom ''Zunwang Rangyi'' ({{lang|zh-Hant|尊王攘夷}}; {{lit}} "Revere the King, Expel the Barbarians"). During the [[Spring and Autumn period]] of China, Chancellor [[:en:Guan Zhong|Guan Zhong]] of [[Qi (state)|Qi]] initiated a policy known as ''Zunwang Rangyi'', in reference to the [[Zhou kings]].<ref name=po5-65>{{cite book | last=Poo | first=Mu-chou | title=Enemies of Civilization | year=2005 | publisher=State University of New York Press | location=Albany | isbn=0-7914-6364-8 | page=65}}</ref> Adopting and adhering to it, [[:en:Duke Huan of Qi|Duke Huan of Qi]] assembled the Chinese feudal lords to strike down the threat of barbarians from China.<ref>{{cite book | last=Tillman | first=Hoyt Cleveland | title=Utilitarian Confucianism: Ch'en Liang's Challenge to Chu Hsi | year=1982 | publisher=Harvard University Press | location=Cambridge | isbn=0-674-93176-9 | page=64}}</ref> For it, [[:en:Confucius|Confucius]] himself praised Guan Zhong for the preservation of Chinese civilization through the example of the [[:en:Hua-Yi distinction|contrast]] in the hairstyles and [[:en:Hanfu|clothing styles]] between them and barbaric peoples.<ref name=po5-65/> Through the ''[[:en:Analects|Analects]]'' of Confucius, the Chinese expression came to be transmitted to Japan as ''sonnō jōi''.<ref>{{cite book | last=Holcombe | first=Charles | title=A History of East Asia: From the Origins of Civilization to the Twenty-first Century | year=2010 | publisher=Cambridge University Press | location=Cambridge | isbn=978-0-521-73164-5 | page=216}}</ref>
== Philosophy == The origin of the philosophy as used in Japan can be traced to the Confucian classic the Gongyang Commentary of the ''Chunqiu''. The Tokugawa shogunate promulgated the Zhu Xi school of Neo-Confucianism (''Shushi-gaku''), which interpreted the ''Chunqiu'' using this concept. 17th-century Confucian scholars [[Yamazaki Ansai]] and [[Yamaga Sokō]] wrote on the sanctity of the [[:en:Imperial House of Japan|Imperial House of Japan]] and its superiority to the ruling houses of other nations. These ideas were expanded by [[:en:Kokugaku|Kokugaku]] scholar [[:en:Motoori Norinaga|Motoori Norinaga]], and seen in Takenouchi Shikibu's theory of absolute loyalty to the [[:en:Emperor of Japan|Emperor of Japan]] ([[:ja:尊皇論|尊皇論]] ''sonnōron''), that implied that less loyalty should be given to the ruling Tokugawa shogunate.
[[:en:Mitogaku|Mitogaku]] scholar [[:en:Aizawa Seishisai|Aizawa Seishisai]] introduced the term ''sonnō jōi'' into modern Japanese in his work ''Shinron'' in 1825, where ''sonnō'' was regarded as the reverence expressed by the Tokugawa Shogunate to the emperor and ''jōi'' was the [[History of Roman Catholicism in Japan#Persecution and martyrdom|proscription of Christianity]].
''Sonnō jōi'' was an [[:en:anti-imperialist|anti-imperialist]] expression of [[Western imperialism]] before Japan transitioned to imperialism.<ref>{{cite book |editor=Viren Murthy |title=Pan-Asianism and the Legacy of the Chinese Revolution |page=25 |date=2023 |publisher=University of Chicago Press}}</ref>
