{{Short description|Nationalist slogan in 1850s Japan}}{{refimprove|date=September 2013}} {{Italic title|reason=}} [[File:Yokohama-Sumo-Wrestler-Defeating-a-Foreigner-1861-Ipposai-Yoshifuji.png|thumb|An 1861 image expressing the ''Jōi'' ({{lang|ja|攘夷}}, "Expel the Barbarians") sentiment]] {{nihongo|2=[[:wikt:尊|尊]][[:wikt:王|王]][[:wikt:攘|攘]][[:wikt:夷|夷]]|3='''Sonnō jōi'''|4="revere the Emperor, expel the barbarians"}} was a ''[[:en:Yojijukugo|Yojijukugo]]'' (four-character compound) phrase used as the rallying cry and [[slogan]] of a [[:en:political movement|political movement]] in [[:en:Japan|Japan]] in the 1850s and 1860s, during the [[:en:Bakumatsu|Bakumatsu]] period. Based on [[:en:Neo-Confucianism|Neo-Confucianism]] and [[:en:Kokugaku|Japanese nativism]], the movement sought to overthrow the [[Tokugawa shogunate]] and restore the power of the [[:en:Emperor of Japan|Emperor of Japan]]. {{Infobox Chinese | t = 尊王攘夷 | kanji = 尊王攘夷 | kana = そんのうじょうい | romaji = Sonnō jōi | p = Zunwang Rangyi | j = zyun1 wong4 joeng4 ji4 }}
